\subtree{
\title{Commands}
\pre{\startverb
# Deploy contract
aptos move publish --package-dir hyperbolic_bulk

# Store entropy
aptos move run --function-id 'hyperbolic_bulk::entropy_triads::store_entropy' \
  --args u64:24634579 u256:0x9577dd1cea89307d u256:0x8219ed722cbf7d6a

# Form conserved triad
aptos move run --function-id 'hyperbolic_bulk::entropy_triads::form_conserved_triad' \
  --args u64:0 u64:1 u64:2 'vector<u8>:skill1' 'vector<u8>:skill2' 'vector<u8>:skill3'

# Query stats
aptos move view --function-id 'hyperbolic_bulk::entropy_triads::get_stats'
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{The Bulk-Boundary Insight}
\p{\strong{Why "hyperbolic"?}}

\p{In AdS/CFT, the hyperbolic (anti-de Sitter) bulk contains more information than the flat boundary. Similarly:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Bulk}: Full entropy (drand × eeg × vrf), all triads, all proofs}
\li{\strong{Boundary}: Projected observables (colors, skill names, agent states)}
}

\p{The boundary is a \em{lossy projection} of the bulk. But GF(3) conservation is preserved across the projection—it's a \strong{geometric invariant}.}

\p{\strong{Reafference as Holography}:}

\ul{
\li{When prediction = observation, the boundary faithfully represents the bulk}
\li{"Loopy strange" = holographic consistency (no information loss)}
\li{"Exafference" = external perturbation (bulk ≠ boundary)}
}
}

